definition.value: An alcohol where the hydroxy group is attached to a saturated carbon atom adjacent to a double bond (R groups may be H, organyl, etc.).
An aliphatic alcohol where the hydroxy carbon is beta to a double bond.
An N-oxide where there are three organic groups bonded to the nitrogen atom.
A steroidal acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 7alpha,12alpha-3-oxochol-4-en-24-oic acid.
A ketooctose derivative that is D-glycero-D-altro-octulose carrying a single phosphate substituent at position 8.
A steroidal acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 12alpha-hydroxy-3-oxochola-4,6-dien-24-oic acid.
Any carboxylic acid in which the carbon bearing the carboxy group is substituted by a bromine.
A member of the class of tetracyclines with formula C22H22N2O9 that is an intermediate in the biosynthesis of oxytetracycline by Streptomyces rimosus.
A phenolate anion obtained by deprotonation of one of the phenolic hydroxy groups of any 2-acyl-4-prenylphloroglucinol.
A phenolate anion obtained by deprotonation of one of the phenolic hydroxy groups of any 2-acylphloroglucinol.
A trisaccharide consisting of beta-D-glucopyranosyl, alpha-L-rhamnopyranosyl and D-glucopyranosyl residues connected in sequence by (1->4) and (1->3) links, respectively.
A carbohydrate acid anion that results from the deprotonation of the carboxylic acid group of beta-D-Delta(4)-GlcpA-(1->4)-beta-D-Glcp-(1->4)-alpha-L-Rhap-(1->3)-D-Glcp. The major species at pH 7.3.
A phenolate anion resulting from the deprotonation is of the hydroxy group at position 4 of 3,4,6-trichlorocatechol. The major microspecies at pH 7.3.
An imidazoindole that is 9H-imidazo[1,2-a]indole which is substituted at positions 2, 3, 7, and 9 by cyano, amino, 4-methylpiperazin-1-yl, and oxo groups, respectively.
An imidazoindole that is 9H-imidazo[1,2-a]indole which is substituted at positions 2, 3, and 9 by cyano, amino, and oxo groups, respectively.
An allylic alcohol in which the carbon atom that links the double bond to the hydroxy group is also attached to two hydrogens.
A mycolate ester formed by esterification of (21E)-3-hydroxy-35-[(icosan-2-yl)oxy]-35-oxo-2-pentacosylpentatriacont-21-enoic acid with the 6-OH of D-glucose; produced by Mycobacterium phlei.
An allylic alcohol in which the carbon atom that links the double bond to the hydroxy group is also attached to one other carbon and one hydrogen.
An allylic alcohol in which the carbon atom that links the double bond to the hydroxy group is also attached to two other carbons (R4,R5 =/= H).
An amino acid betaine that is D-proline zwitterion in which both of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen are replaced by methyl groups.
An 1,3-thiazolemonocarboxylic acid that is ADP in which one of the diphosphate hydrogens has been replaced by a 2-(2-carboxy-4-methyl-1,3-thiazol-5-yl)ethyl group.
An organic cationic group obtained by protonation of any peptide group; major species at pH 7.3.
A modified linear (1->4)-alpha-D-glucan
An inorganic nanoparticle consisting of copper(II) oxide.
A nanoparticle composed of poly(styrene).
A nanoparticle composed of graphene.
An L-cysteine derivative obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of anthranilic acid with the side-chain thiol group of L-cysteine.
A member of the class of prostaglandins G that is 9,11-epidioxyprosta-5,13,17-trienoic acid carrying an additional hydroperoxy substituent at the 15S-position.
A member of the class of prostaglandins H that is 9,11-epidioxyprosta-5,13,17-trienoic acid carrying an additional hydroxy substituent at the 15S-position.
An ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the primary amino group of N-acetylcadaverine. The major microspecies at pH 7.3.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of N-acetyl-L-methione with the amino group of L-asparagine.
An L-cysteine derivative obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of octanoic acid with the side-chain thiol group of L-cysteine.
A triacyl lipopeptide that is N-palmitoyl-Cys-Ser-Lys-Lys-Lys-Lys in which the side-chain thiol hydrogen on the Cys residue has been replaced by a 2,3-bis(palmitoyloxy)propyl group.
A tetrahydrofolyl glutamate consisting of a 10-formyltetrahydrofolyl group linked via an amide bond to a poly(gamma-glutamyl chain)
An ionic macromolecule obtained by global deprotonation of the carboxy groups of 10-formyltetrahydrofolyl-(Glu)n. Major microspecies at pH 7.3
A fatty acyl-CoA(4-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate functions of 2-hydroxyhexacosanoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A 5-oxo-2-furylacetic acid that is muconolactone substituted at position 5 by a chloro group.
Any oxo fatty acid in which an oxo substituent is located at position 3.
A hydroxy polyunsaturated fatty acid that is (6Z,8E,14Z)-icosatrienoic acid carrying hydroxy and oxo substituents at positions 5 and 12 respectively.
A leukotriene with formula C23H39NO6S that results from the metabilism of leukotriene B4 by human keratinocytes.
An aminoimidazole that is 1H-imidazole which is substituted by amino groups at positions 1 and 5, and by a cyano group at position 4.
An aminoimidazole that is 5-amino-1H-imidazole which is substituted at positions 1 and 4 by aminocarbonyl and cyano groups, respectively.
An aminoimidazole that is 5-amino-1H-imidazole which is substituted at positions 1 and 4 by anilino and cyano groups, respectively.
An aminoimidazole that is 5-amino-1H-imidazole which is substituted at positions 1 and 4 by benzoyl and cyano groups, respectively.
An O-acylcarnitine in which the acyl group is specified as (4E,7E,10E,13E,16E)-docosapentaenoyl.
An O-acylcarnitine in which the acyl group is specified as (4E,7E,10E,13E,16E,19E)-docosahexaenoyl.
An organic heterohexacyclic compound that is soladulcidine carrying an acetoxy substituent at position 23
A glycosylglycerol derivative that is 1,2-ditetradecanoylglycerol in which the hydroxy hydrogen at position 3 has been replaced by a 6-sulfoquinovopyranosyl residue.
A phosphatidylethanolamine in which the two acyl groups contain a total of 38 carbons and 6 double bonds.
A phosphatidylethanolamine in which the two acyl groups contain a total of 40 carbons and 7 double bonds.
